a **command** consists of a prompt, the command, options, arguments
* prompt
  * supplied by the terminal, user$

# Shortcuts
new tab: ctrl+shift+t
cancel: control + c
sol: ^A
eod: ^E
clear line: ^U
paste: ^ + shift + V
clear: clear or ^L
exit: ^D
~ : shortcut for home ~/whatever/
.. : one up
. : current directory

# Commands

combining commands:
* ./configure ; make ; make install
* ./configure && make && make install

manual: pulls up help files/documentation on commands/programs
* man <command>
* q to quit

ls: list all files and directories
* ls
* ls wildcard.<extension>
* ls -a list hidden files
* ls -l <filename>  outputs additional info
* ls -rtl reverse time modified long
* ls -h  human readable

cd: change directory
* cd <location>
* cd - previous directory

echo: prints to screen
* echo "txt" >
  * appends to a file

cat: combine contents or view contents
* cat <file>


diff: compare two files
* diff <file1> <file2>

touch: change  mondify time or create empty file1
* touch <filename>
* touch echo.txt mv echo.txt bar.txt cp bar.txt baz.txt

! bang: reruns the last commands
* !echo would run last echo command

# File Manipulation

mkdir: makes a directory
* mkdir <foldername>

move: can be used to move or rename files
* mv <filename> <newfilename>
* mv <filename>  newfolder/folder
* mv -i prompt before overwrite
* mv -n won't overwrite
* mv --strip-trailing-slashes [source] [dest]
* mv -u only if newer
* mv -b creates backup with~


copy: creates a copy of a file
* cp <filename> <newfilename>
* cp -r recursive, copies all files

Append to file
* >> <txt>

cat: combine contents or view contents
* cat <file>

# File Inspection
head: shows first 10 lines
* head <filename>

tail: shows last 10 lines
* tail <filename>
* tailing the log file
  * tail -f <file>

less: opens a file for searching
* /<searchterm>
  * n(ext) N(previous)
* ^f forward
* ^b backward
* G move to eof
* 1G back to beginning

grep: search for a string in a file
* grep <term> <file>
* -i removes case sensitivity
* -r recursive
grep -ri <term> <location>

# Other

cURl: transfers data from or to a server
